@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Privacy";
}

<section class="about">
    <header class="mixer__intro">
        <h1 class="mixer__title">Privacy</h1>
        <p class="mixer__subtitle">What this tool does and doesn't collect.</p>
    </header>

    <article class="about__card">
        <h2 class="about__heading">The short version</h2>
        <p>
            This is a small, non‑commercial hobby tool. It has <strong>no accounts, no sign‑up,
            no tracking, no analytics, and no advertising</strong>. It doesn't ask you for any
            personal information, and it doesn't sell or share data with anyone.
        </p>
    </article>

    <article class="about__card">
        <h2 class="about__heading">What the app stores</h2>
        <ul class="about__list">
            <li><strong>No cookies.</strong> The page doesn't set cookies or use local storage.</li>
            <li><strong>No account or profile data.</strong> There's nothing to log in to.</li>
            <li>
                Your product and ingredient choices are sent as part of the page address
                (e.g. <code>?product=og_kush&amp;count=4</code>) so the result can be shown — they
                aren't stored or associated with you.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="about__card">
        <h2 class="about__heading">Server logs</h2>
        <p>
            Like any website, when you open a page the web server (or its hosting provider) may
            automatically record standard technical access data — such as your IP address, the
            browser you use, and the date and time. This happens only to run the site and keep it
            secure, isn't used to identify you, and isn't combined with anything else. If the tool
            is run locally on your own machine, no such data leaves your computer.
        </p>
    </article>

    <article class="about__card">
        <h2 class="about__heading">Third parties</h2>
        <p>
            The page loads only its own files — no external fonts, scripts, or trackers — so
            opening it doesn't send your data to any third‑party service.
        </p>
    </article>
</section>
